fr:mainmatter.html:p:
The key new ideas in this lecture are the idea of a matrix, and of the logic determined by a matrix.
We've seen four examples of this idea, and used them to name four particular logics:

designating \mathsf {\mathbf {T}} in the Boolean structure gives us a matrix that determines classical logic;

designating \mathsf {\mathbf {T}} in the strong Kleene structure gives us a matrix that determines the logic K3;

designating \mathsf {\mathbf {T}} and \mathsf {\mathbf {*}} in the strong Kleene structure gives us a matrix that determines the logic LP; and

designating \mathsf {\mathbf {T}} and \mathsf {\mathbf {B}} in the Dunn-Belnap structure gives us a matrix that determines the logic FDE.

Our standard language for this semester has:

infinitely many atomic sentences, written p, q, r, and so on;

three binary connectives: \land , \lor , and \rightarrow ;

one unary connective: \neg ; and

two nullary connectives: \top , \bot .
